---
title: "How to Build an Optimization Layer Into Your Core Business Systems"
date: "2023-03-14"
summary: "Build an optimization layer between tools and team. Learn the structural decisions that make system-wide improvements repeatable across workflows."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Optimization"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your core systems run the business. Your optimization layer decides whether those systems get better over time or calcify into overhead.

An optimization layer is a thin structure you place between your existing tools and the people who operate them. It does not replace your CRM, your ERP, or your support queue. It wraps around them and forces three questions into every [workflow](/process). What is the input. What is the output. What changed between last time and this time.

Most teams skip this. They buy another tool instead. Then they wonder why the new tool added cost without adding clarity.

Start with one system. Pick the one where delays hurt the most. Map its inputs and outputs on paper. Do not start with software. Start with a whiteboard and a timer. Time each handoff. You will find that 40 to 60 percent of the wait time sits between systems, not inside them.

That gap is where your optimization layer lives.

The layer needs three components. First, a measurement point at every handoff. Second, a weekly review that compares those measurements against the previous four weeks. Third, a single owner who is responsible for flagging when a handoff drifts more than 20 percent from its baseline.

Measurement points are simple. A timestamp when a ticket moves from sales to onboarding. A count of how many times a support case gets reopened. A ratio of completed tasks to tasks created per week. These numbers already exist in your tools. The optimization layer surfaces them.

The weekly review is where most teams fail. They collect numbers and never compare them. Comparison is what turns data into signal. Set a recurring 30-minute meeting. Same time every week. Same three people. Review five numbers. Decide if any of them moved enough to act on.

The single owner matters because shared responsibility means no responsibility. This person does not fix the problems. They surface them. They send a two-sentence update every Friday. Numbers moved here. We should look at this one.

You do not need a new platform to do this. A shared spreadsheet works for the first three months. A dashboard tool works after that. The structure matters more than the tool.

Here is the hard part. The optimization layer will surface problems your team does not want to see. Handoffs that take twice as long as people assume. Steps that exist because someone left the company two years ago. Metrics that have been drifting upward for six months while everyone focused on revenue.

That discomfort is the point. The layer exists to make invisible friction visible. If your optimization layer makes everyone comfortable, you built a reporting dashboard instead.

Start with one system. Measure three handoffs. Review for four weeks. Then expand. The layer grows one system at a time. After six months you will have a structure that catches problems before your customers do.

The companies that compound are the ones that build this layer early. Not when the pain is obvious. Before it is. Because by the time the pain is obvious, you have already lost margin you will never recover.
